            "explanation": "The <pre>main</pre> element represents the dominant content of the document body, while <pre>article</pre> represents a self-contained composition that could be distributed independently. This creates a clear semantic hierarchy.\n\n[CODE]// Semantic hierarchy explanation:\n\n// main - primary content of the document\n// â†³ article - independent, self-contained content\n//   â†³ header - article-specific header\n//   â†³ content - article body\n//   â†³ footer - article-specific footer\n// â†³ aside - related but separate content\n\n// Multiple articles within main\n<main>\n  <article>\n    <h2>First Article</h2>\n    <p>Content...</p>\n  </article>\n  \n  <article>\n    <h2>Second Article</h2>\n    <p>Content...</p>\n  </article>\n  \n  <aside>\n    <!-- Content tangentially related to main content -->\n  </aside>\n</main>\n\n// When to use article vs section:\n// - article: standalone content (blog posts, news articles, comments)\n// - section: thematic grouping of content (chapters, tabbed content)\n\n// Nested articles for complex content\n<article>\n  <h1>Main Article</h1>\n  <p>Introduction...</p>\n  \n  <section>\n    <h2>Chapter 1</h2>\n    <p>Chapter content...</p>\n    \n    <article>\n      <h3>Case Study</h3>\n      <p>Case study that could stand alone...</p>\n    </article>\n  </section>\n</article>[/CODE]\n\nThis semantic structure helps search engines understand content relationships and assists screen readers in navigating the document effectively.",
